"A grid of cells. Each cell is dead or alive. Each generation, every
cell looks at its eight neighbors and follows one rule:

- If I'm alive and I have 2 or 3 alive neighbors, I stay alive.
- If I'm dead and I have exactly 3 alive neighbors, I come to life.
- Otherwise I die (or stay dead).

That is Conway's Game of Life. Four bullet points. The rule is
completely local — each cell only sees its neighbors — and completely
deterministic — same state, same next state. Yet from these four
bullet points emerges a computational zoo containing gliders,
spaceships, oscillators, glider guns, and (it turns out) an
implementation of a universal Turing machine. Life is a whole world
built on a rule you can teach to an eight-year-old in three minutes.

This chapter builds Life, spawns famous patterns, then generalizes to
arbitrary cellular rules (`B368/S245`, `HighLife`, `Seeds`) so you can
invent your own.

---

## 8.1 Conway's Game of Life, minimally

```scheme
(define (life cols rows)
  (world/reset!)
  (conway-init cols rows)
  (conway-spawn-glider   10 10)      ;; classic 5-cell glider
  (conway-spawn-gosper    2  2)      ;; the glider gun
  (conway-spawn-lwss     40 20)      ;; lightweight spaceship
  (on-frame
    (lambda (t)
      (when (= 0 (modulo t 4))       ;; step every 4 frames
        (conway-step))
      (canvas-paint!))))

(life 60 40)
```

Six lines and you have Life running. `conway-init` allocates the
grid. `conway-spawn-*` places named patterns at (x, y). `conway-step`
advances one generation. `canvas-paint!` draws the current state to
the framebuffer.

Watch the glider glide diagonally. Watch the gun periodically shoot
another glider. Watch the LWSS travel horizontally. Watch collisions
create static debris. Watch the gliders from the gun crash into the
LWSS's path.

## 8.2 The rule made explicit

Motoi Scheme's `canvas-rule` gives you the full B/S notation. Life is
`B3/S23` — Born on 3 neighbors, Survive on 2 or 3.

```scheme
;; Set an alternate rule live.
(canvas-rule-set! 'B3/S23)     ;; Conway's Life (default)
(canvas-rule-set! 'B36/S23)    ;; HighLife — has a replicator
(canvas-rule-set! 'B2/S)       ;; Seeds — nothing survives; life sparks
(canvas-rule-set! 'B368/S245)  ;; Morley — larger patterns
```

Try each. `Seeds` looks like fireworks — patterns light up briefly
and go dark. `HighLife` has a replicator, a pattern that grows into
two copies of itself. `Morley` supports much larger stable structures.

The formal recipe for a rule is: given the count of alive neighbors,
either be born (if you were dead) or survive (if you were alive).
There are 2^18 possible B/S rules. Most are boring. Life is on a
narrow ridge where enough patterns die that things stay interesting
and enough survive that things stay complex — the 'edge of chaos.'

## 8.3 A random soup

Start with a random 30%-alive grid and see what emerges.

```scheme
(define (soup cols rows density)
  (conway-init cols rows)
  (canvas-spawn-pattern 'random density)
  (on-frame
    (lambda (t)
      (when (= 0 (modulo t 3))
        (conway-step))
      (canvas-paint!))))

(soup 80 60 0.3)
```

The first few generations are chaotic. Cells die in droves. Then the
survivors stabilize into a scattering of still lifes (blocks, beehives,
loaves), oscillators (blinkers, toads, beacons), and the occasional
glider that migrates across the field until it hits something.

If you leave it running for thousands of steps, the population
plateau. You can count with `conway-live-count`.

```scheme
;; Plot population over time.
(define pop-history '())
(on-frame
  (lambda (t)
    (when (= 0 (modulo t 3))
      (conway-step)
      (set! pop-history (cons (conway-live-count) pop-history)))
    (canvas-paint!)
    (when (= 0 (modulo t 60))
      (plot/line (reverse (take pop-history 100)) :region '(0 250 200 100)))))
```

You will see a chaotic transient, then oscillations, then a plateau.
This is a shape you'll see again and again in emergent systems.

## 8.4 Beyond binary: 3-state and aged automata

`grid-step-3state` supports rules with three states — dead, sick,
alive, say — where transitions can be more like an infection model.

```scheme
(grid-init 60 40 3)
(grid-step-3state
  :on-alive  (lambda (n) (if (or (= n 2) (= n 3)) 'alive 'sick))
  :on-sick   (lambda (n) 'dead)
  :on-dead   (lambda (n) (if (= n 3) 'alive 'dead)))
```

Or age-based, where cells count how long they've been alive:

```scheme
(grid-init 60 40 :aged #t)
(grid-step-aged :max-age 8)
```

Older cells might be more likely to die, or to reproduce, or to
change color. This models things like moss growth or wildfire
spread better than plain binary Life.

## 8.5 Design your own rule

The moment where cellular automata become play: change the rule and
see what happens.

```scheme
;; Custom rule: born on 4-5, survive on 3-6.
(canvas-rule-set! (make-rule '(4 5) '(3 4 5 6)))
```

Some rules explode into complete chaos. Some rules die immediately.
Some rules produce fluid-like blobs. Some produce patterns that grow
forever in a diamond shape. Most produce something boring. A few
produce something like Life.

There is a scientific project called Wolfram's classification (Class
I: dies quickly; Class II: static or periodic; Class III: chaotic;
Class IV: complex, at the edge of chaos). Conway's Life is Class IV.
Most rules are Class I, II, or III. Class IV is a narrow band, and
discovering a new Class IV rule is a small joy.

## 8.6 Physics as computation, computation as physics

Cellular automata are physics-flavored — cells, neighbors, local
rules, discrete time. They are also fully computational — you can
build a universal Turing machine out of Life patterns (it's been
done, at enormous scale). The point of the equivalence is that
'physics' and 'computation' are not opposed. A cellular automaton
IS a discrete physics; a physics IS a continuous cellular automaton.
Whichever direction you approach from, the shape is the same:
neighbors, rules, iteration, emergence.

Real physics does exactly the same thing at Planck scale, we suspect.
A cell (which is 'a bit of space') updates based on its immediate
neighborhood (the field values it's coupled to). The rules are the
laws of physics. The emergence is everything — atoms, chemistry, life,
minds. You are the long-term behavior of a cellular automaton whose
rules are the Standard Model plus general relativity, and whose
initial condition is the Big Bang. Life is not a metaphor; it's a
scale model.

---

## 8.7 The four routing patterns in cellular automata

**Composition.** `conway-step` is composed: for every cell, count
neighbors, apply rule, write next-generation cell. You can compose
`grid-step-with-noise` on top by flipping a small number of cells
randomly each step — models mutation.

**Orchestration.** The frame loop orchestrates: step every N frames,
paint, sample population. A longer orchestration is 'run for 10000
generations, snapshot every 1000, save snapshots, compare.'

**In-routing.** Click events route to `canvas-cell-toggle` — the user
paints in patterns. Keyboard events like 'g for glider' route to
`canvas-spawn-pattern`.

**Routing.** Cell states route to the framebuffer as filled squares.
Population time-series routes to a plot. 'Discovered a new stable
pattern' events could route to Cortex for the pattern library. A
The runtime reasoning chain: 'user asked what rule this is; I ran it for
100 steps; I compared to known rules; it matches HighLife; I answer
"HighLife (B36/S23)."' Chain-of-inference over sim behavior.

---

## 8.8 Common desktop tasks

An operator running a game-store display asked the runtime: 'if I want a
demo screen showing something visually interesting for 12 hours
without repeating, what should I run?' A random-soup Life run
satisfies both — chaotic transient, always-fresh gliders, no repeats
for hundreds of thousands of generations. Ten lines of Motoi Scheme,
one framebuffer, cheap CPU.

## 8.9 Try this

1. Draw a shape with your mouse and let Life run. Does anything
   survive?
2. Run HighLife until you see a replicator. It looks like a small
   cross that splits into two.
3. Invent a rule: `B234/S345`. What class is it?
4. Add color: each cell is red if it just came alive, fades to blue
   as it survives, black when dead.
5. Cross-breed two rules: half the grid runs Life, half runs Seeds.
   What happens at the boundary?

## 8.10 Pitfalls

**Boundary conditions.** The edge of the grid matters. Fixed
(dead-outside), wrap-around (torus), and reflecting all produce
different long-term behavior. `conway-init` defaults to wrap-around;
change with `(conway-init cols rows :boundary 'fixed)`.

**Stepping too fast.** If you step every frame at 60 fps, patterns
move too fast to enjoy. Every 4 frames (15 gps) is nicer.

**Discovery vs replication.** Every rule you invent has been tried by
someone. That is fine — you're building intuition. The pattern zoos
online (Appendix E has some) are worth browsing.

---

Next: particle systems. Many small entities with lifetimes. Sparks,
smoke, water. All the same physics.")
